\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {9}{\ignorespaces  Critical population sizes $N_c$ as a function of selection strength $w$ for the SD observable $H_{SD}$. Moran process simulations with ($\gamma =0.2$, $\beta =0.1$, standard RPS parameters) Points are simulated estimate of $N_c$ by approximating $\langle \Delta H \rangle $ over a single update step, averaged over $10^8$ realizations. Curve is analytical prediction when setting equation\nobreakspace  {}\ref  {eq:delta_h_sd} equal to 0. Close agreement, and drift reversal clear in both analytical result and simulated results.}}{11}{figure.9}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:n_c_against_w}{{9}{11}{Critical population sizes $N_c$ as a function of selection strength $w$ for the SD observable $H_{SD}$. Moran process simulations with ($\gamma =0.2$, $\beta =0.1$, standard RPS parameters) Points are simulated estimate of $N_c$ by approximating $\langle \Delta H \rangle $ over a single update step, averaged over $10^8$ realizations. Curve is analytical prediction when setting equation~\ref {eq:delta_h_sd} equal to 0. Close agreement, and drift reversal clear in both analytical result and simulated results}{figure.9}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {10}{\ignorespaces  Time series of the fraction of $+$ strategy for three interaction processes: Moran (red), local update (blue), and local Fermi (green). Dashed lines are the deterministic replicator equation solutions for each process. Large $N$ ($N=100000$) simulations closely follow the deterministic trajectory with small noise deviations. Low $N$ ($N=200$) simulations, averaged over 1000 realisations, exhibit drift reversal. Trajectories move away from the deterministic fixed point and the $+$ fraction converges towards zero, as the population ends up playing purely RPS ($q \rightarrow 0$), opposite to the replicator prediction.}}{11}{figure.10}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:drift_time_series}{{10}{11}{Time series of the fraction of $+$ strategy for three interaction processes: Moran (red), local update (blue), and local Fermi (green). Dashed lines are the deterministic replicator equation solutions for each process. Large $N$ ($N=100000$) simulations closely follow the deterministic trajectory with small noise deviations. Low $N$ ($N=200$) simulations, averaged over 1000 realisations, exhibit drift reversal. Trajectories move away from the deterministic fixed point and the $+$ fraction converges towards zero, as the population ends up playing purely RPS ($q \rightarrow 0$), opposite to the replicator prediction}{figure.10}{}}
